'''Tamal Bandyopadhyay''' is an Indian business journalist, known for his weekly column on banking and finance Banker's Trust published in ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'', an Indian business daily by [[HT Media Ltd]]. He has authored four books namely ''From Lehman to Demonetization: A Decade of Disruptions, Reforms and Misadventures'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/0vN3UVeZADZIuImLrZL9jL/That-dreaded-word-Resign.html |title=That dreaded word: Resign - Livemint }}</ref> ''Bandhan: The Making of a Bank'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/recliner/bandhan-the-making-of-a-bank-highlights-chandra-shekhar-ghoshs-focus-vision/43669/1|title=Bandhan: The Making of a Bank highlights Chandra Shekhar Ghosh's focus, vision|website=forbesindia.com}}</ref> ''Sahara: The Untold Story'' and ''A Bank for the Buck''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2012/11/27/an-indian-banks-success-story/ |title=An Indian Bank's Success Story – India Real Time – WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=27 November 2012 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>

==Life and career==
A student of English literature (a postgraduate from [[Calcutta University]]), Tamal Bandyopadhyay began his career in journalism as a trainee journalist with ''[[Times of India]]'', in [[Mumbai]] in 1985. Subsequently, he has worked with four national financial dailies: ''[[The Economic Times]]'', ''[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]'', ''[[Business Standard]]'', and as a member of the founding team of ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]'' in February 2007, going on to serve as its deputy managing editor and later as a consulting editor till September 2018. Currently he is a consulting editor of ''[[Business Standard]]'',<ref name=bs>{{cite news |title=Business Standard's consulting editor in LinkedIn Top Voices in India list |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/business-editor-s-consulting-editor-in-linkedin-s-top-voices-in-india-list-118111301660_1.html |accessdate=21 November 2018 |work=Business Standard India |date=13 November 2018}}</ref> a business daily where he served as deputy resident editor in Mumbai before joining ''[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]''.

He is also a senior adviser to [[Jana Small Finance Bank]]<ref name=bs /> and an adviser at [[Bandhan Bank]] from August 2014.

Bandyopadhyay is popular for his weekly column on banking and finance called ''Banker's Trust'', published every Monday. His frequent blog ''Banker's Trust Real Time'' on [[LiveMint]].com analyses major developments in the financial sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/vsp7RPTxjxRq9OYcOMZJhJ/How-RBI-blocked-evergreening-of-overseas-loans.html |title=How RBI blocked evergreening of overseas loans |publisher=LiveMint |date=23 April 2014 |accessdate=13 May 2014 |last1=Bandyopadhyay |first1=Tamal }}</ref>

Between April and November 2011, he ran a 32 episode series on Bloomberg India TV, called Banker's Trust, where senior central bankers, commercial bankers, and economists were interviewed every week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vheqWC5vep8 |title=Banker's Trust with Tamal Bandyopadhyay: Part 1 |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>

==Bibliography==
* {{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/823821380 |title=A bank for the buck: The new bank movement & the untold story of the making of India's most valued bank |date=2013}}
* ''Anupam Meenrashi'' (2014)
* {{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/883179164 |title=Sahara: The untold story |isbn=8184955464 |location=Ahmedabad |oclc=883179164}}
* ''Bandhan: The Making of a Bank'' (2016)
* {{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1017756529 |title=From Lehman to demonetization : a decade of disruptions, reforms and misadventures |isbn=9789387326392 |location=Gurgaon, Haryana, India |oclc=1017756529}}

Releasing Tamal's first book, ''[[A Bank for the Buck]]'', in November 2012, then finance minister [[P Chidambaram]] said, "In a period of great financial illiteracy, it's refreshing to have a book written by somebody very literate about matters relating to finance". In his foreword to the book, former governor of Reserve Bank of India, [[Y. Venugopal Reddy]], wrote, "It's a sort of recent oral history of a financial institution. Tamal has set a new trend in the dissemination of knowledge."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDiGu8fW5js |title=P Chidambaram talks about the book A Bank for the Buck |publisher=YouTube |date=30 November 2012 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>

Tamal's second book, ''Sahara: The Untold Story'', details the beginnings and the current day working of the secretive Sahara India Parivar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bandyopadhyay|first1=Tamal|title=Excerpt from the book "Sahara: The Untold Story"|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/book-review---sahara-the-untold-story/1/201081.html|website=businesstoday.intoday.in|publisher=Jaico Publishers|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> The book was well researched, with interviews with people concerned, including [[Subrata Roy]]. In December 2013, the [[Sahara India Pariwar]], moved [[Calcutta High Court]], got a stay on the publication of the book and filed a Rs 2&nbsp; billion defamation suit against the author and its publisher, Jaico Publishing House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/sahara-slaps-rs-200-crore-libel-suit-against-mint-scribe-for-untold-story/article1-1172565.aspx |title=Sahara slaps Rs. 200-crore libel suit against Mint scribe for 'untold story' |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=13 January 2014 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref> In April 2014, the parties reached an out of court settlement, following which the book carries a disclaimer by Sahara which says, among other things, the book has "defamatory content" – something unprecedented in Indian publishing history, as narrated in [[Sue the Messenger]] by [[Subir Ghosh]], with [[Paranjoy Guha Thakurta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/jAsA4cFwmfK17Znzy8Q1MJ/Sahara-withdraws-case-against-Mint-journalists-book.html |title=Sahara withdraws case against 'Mint' journalist's book |publisher=Livemint |date=25 April 2014 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>

He has also published a book of poems in Bengali ''Anupam Meenrashi'' in January 2014.

Tamal Bandyopadhyay is also a contributor to The Oxford Companion to Economics in India, the first comprehensive and far-reaching compendium of short essays of its kind, covering a vast range of themes related to the contemporary Indian economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrmlonline.com/?page=shop/flypage&product_id=2296758|title=The Oxford Companion to Economics in India}}</ref>

In his foreword to ''Bandhan: The Making of a Bank'', [[Kaushik Basu]], chief economist of the World Bank, has written, "Tamal Bandyopadhyay is a gifted storyteller, who combines the sharp vision of a finance expert with the journalist's skill for observation and narration."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=yIc_DAAAQBAJ&pg=PT8&lpg=PT8&dq=%22tamal+Bandyopadhyay+is+a+gifted+storyteller%22&source=bl&ots=ivPYmpA-Ae&sig=vkITaSyf6xoGRK7vBfxImjK-NjY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjj34jVhazYAhWC3SYKHeXMCKMQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=%22tamal%20Bandyopadhyay%20is%20a%20gifted%20storyteller%22&f=false|title=books.google.co.in}}</ref>

[[K. V. Kamath]], the chief of the New Development Bank of BRICS countries has written in his foreword to ''From Lehman to Demonetization'', "Tamal has the unique ability to be witty, pithy, sharp and tongue-in-cheek - all at the same time. ... For a long time, he has kept his readers hooked".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=WClADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT13&lpg=PT13&dq=Tamal+has+the+unique+ability+to+be+witty,+pithy,+sharp&source=bl&ots=H7nHq6ygvX&sig=VFo6ugzEdSacoGRSssgja1GTkPs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRs8Shh6zYAhUHq48KHT0PAyYQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=books.google.co.in}}</ref>

==Awards and recognition==

[[LinkedIn]] nominated Tamal Bandyopadhyay for three successive years (2015, 2016 and 2017) as one of the top voices in finance. In 2018, he has been nominated as one of the top 25 voices in India across sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/linkedin-top-voices-2018-india-linkedin-editors-india-/|title=LinkedIn Top Voices 2018: India|website=linkedin.com}}</ref>

He is a recipient of [[Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards|Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Award]] for commentary and interpretative writing for the year 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/ramnath-goenka-excellence-in-journalism-awards-full-winners-list-4991626/|title=Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards: Full list of winners|website=indianexpress.com}}</ref>

